# Example note — rename to `pharmacy-first.md` to activate

This is a template showing the kind of standing triage instruction you can add.
Files ending in `.example` are ignored; rename to a `.md` file to switch it on
(or, better, keep this content in a OneNote page so you can edit it without a
redeploy).

## Pharmacy First — signpost before booking a GP

For patients aged 1 year and over presenting with one of these, offer Pharmacy
First (community pharmacy) before booking a GP appointment, unless a red flag is
present:

- Sore throat
- Sinusitis
- Earache (acute otitis media, ages 1–17)
- Infected insect bite
- Impetigo
- Shingles
- Uncomplicated urinary tract infection (women 16–64)

Suggested wording: "This is something our community pharmacist can assess and
treat today under the NHS Pharmacy First scheme — would you like me to signpost
you there? If it doesn't settle, come back to us."

## Escalate instead of signposting if

- Difficulty breathing or swallowing, drooling, or a muffled "hot potato" voice
- One-sided severe throat swelling, or unable to swallow fluids
- High fever with a rash that does not fade under pressure
- Symptoms lasting longer than the pharmacy pathway allows, or already treated
  without improvement

When in doubt, add to the duty doctor list rather than signposting.
